commit_message:
Fixes API list handling of unscoped tokens

The API list methods were not handling unscoped tokens correctly.
If the API is using the admin_or_owner-policy.yaml policy override file,
and a user used an unscoped token, the API will list objects for all
projects. This patch corrects that issue.
If you are using the default policies, the API handles unscoped tokens
correctly.

Change-Id: I88e64fd5e8a4c709f735be85b85139dbb52e4acd
(cherry picked from commit 9453701fb46f0ad23dae00b3a3792bb379978d0e)

commit_message:
[goal] Migrate sahara tempest plugin jobs to focal

As per victoria cycle testing runtime and community goal[1]
we need to migrate upstream CI/CD to Ubuntu Focal(20.04).

Most of the Tempest jobs will be migrate automatically once devstack
base job start running on Focal(Depends-On).

Stable jobs testing stable branch needs to keep running on their supported
distro version which is bionic from stein till ussuri.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/731207/

[1] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/selected/victoria/migrate-ci-cd-jobs-to-ubuntu-focal.html

Change-Id: I36865eaaad184d55abe6c8dd5f23b537defaf4e8
Story: #2007865
Task: #40216

[{'created': '2020-09-07 12:31:46.000000000', 'message': 'Support libvirt/cpu_models instead of libvirt/cpu_model

The libvirt/cpu_model parameter has been deprecated in nova[1] in
favor of the new parameter cpu_models, so puppet-nova should support
that new parameter.

Note that this change directly removes cpu_model parameter which is
added by the parent change, to avoid a redundant deprecated parameter
created in a single release.

commit_message:
Support libvirt/cpu_models instead of libvirt/cpu_model

The libvirt/cpu_model parameter has been deprecated in nova[1] in
favor of the new parameter, cpu_models, so puppet-nova should support
that new parameter instead of the old one.

Note that this change directly removes cpu_model parameter which is
added by the parent change, to avoid a redundant deprecated parameter
created in a single release.

[1] f80e5f989db7f326e824b671cfe0a8bbb047cfca
Change-Id: Ib8e9ec2e0bde59e72b0ce3639b64d3e8a6ff9eac

commit_message:
Switch to newer openstackdocstheme and reno versions

Switch to openstackdocstheme 2.2.1 and reno 3.1.0 versions. Using
these versions will allow especially:
* Linking from HTML to PDF document
* Allow parallel building of documents
* Fix some rendering problems

Update Sphinx version as well.

Disable openstackdocs_auto_name to use 'project' variable as name.

Set openstackdocs_pdf_link to link to PDF file. Note that
the link to the published document only works on docs.openstack.org
where the PDF file is placed in the top-level html directory. The
site-preview places the PDF in a pdf directory.

Change pygments_style to 'native' since old theme version always used
'native' and the theme now respects the setting and using 'sphinx' can
lead to some strange rendering.

Remove docs requirements from lower-constraints, they are not needed
during install or test but only for docs building.

openstackdocstheme renames some variables, so follow the renames
before the next release removes them. A couple of variables are also
not needed anymore, remove them.

See also
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-discuss/2020-May/014971.html

Change-Id: I131850d2a5c6164dfd48c9c95885d4754b5236c6
(cherry picked from commit 3d105b623d13d8fe6bb4db676196a44ac3db464f)

messages: [{'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2020-09-16 21:48:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2020-09-24 03:54:41.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned\n\nI guess the docs job fixed itself...?'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2020-09-16 21:48:10.000000000', 'message': 'Remove <py3.5 dependencies from requirements.txt

The requirements repo is support python 3.5 as oldest python version
while swift still supports py27.

thus, requirements-check will fail on a couple of lines in swift.  The
check is only run when these files are touched.

The py2.7 packagers we know about aren't depending on upstream
requirements.txt for correctness and aside from all the production
deployments running on py2.7 we only realistically support >=py3.7

There's no good reason for our requirements.txt to be "unspported" by
the openstack requirements check job.  Since they only support >=py3.5
we can change our requirements.txt inline with that.  This should be
fine for everything we could hope to get out of both our
requirements.txt and the check!

Co-Authored-By: Clay Gerrard <clay.gerrard@gmail.com>
Change-Id: Ibf8000498528c401707be8b0b91b8355cd993786
(cherry picked from commit 019bade19cd20aaebb6dd1f423ab2dbb15cd12a1)
'}]
commit_message:
Remove <py3.5 dependencies from requirements.txt

The requirements repo is support python 3.5 as oldest python version
while swift still supports py27.

thus, requirements-check will fail on a couple of lines in swift.  The
check is only run when these files are touched.

The py2.7 packagers we know about aren't depending on upstream
requirements.txt for correctness and aside from all the production
deployments running on py2.7 we only realistically support >=py3.7

There's no good reason for our requirements.txt to be "unspported" by
the openstack requirements check job.  Since they only support >=py3.5
we can change our requirements.txt inline with that.  This should be
fine for everything we could hope to get out of both our
requirements.txt and the check!

Co-Authored-By: Clay Gerrard <clay.gerrard@gmail.com>
Change-Id: Ibf8000498528c401707be8b0b91b8355cd993786
(cherry picked from commit 019bade19cd20aaebb6dd1f423ab2dbb15cd12a1)

commit_message:
Train only: supply the stack name when creating the inventory

The function issues only a warning, that it couldn't generate
the inventory for a non-existing deployment, later on, ansible
also only issues a warning that it can't parse the inventory.
This resulted in iterating over an empty list of hosts and
not removing the host entries from IPA.

Change-Id: I94599322eb8b77f00bd46e0100db4d7beedec536
Resolves: rhbz#1869001
Closes-Bug: #1894904

commit_message:
Lower default verbosity for ansible

Similar to aef369e7b4d38e4ca7eb158d2878e84a4b93e603 however this only
affects the ansible-playbook execution. By default openstack cli sets
verbosity to 1 so we are always running ansible-playbook with a -v. This
can a consequence on the information returned during execution as we may
get extra result data in the output.

Change-Id: I4e1cb6658172a7da5ae5198ba55d47de33282975
(cherry picked from commit e8e2ca479faaf96763ba5b27af06a73ebdb5c6c3)

[{'created': '2020-07-26 22:45:59.000000000', 'message': '[goal] Migrate tempest jobs to focal

As per victoria cycle testing runtime and community goal[1]
we need to migrate upstream CI/CD to Ubuntu Focal(20.04).

Most of the Tempest jobs will be migrate automatically once devstack
base job start running on Focal(Depends-On).

Stable jobs testing stable branch needs to keep running on their supported
distro version which is bionic from stein till ussuri.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/731207/

[1] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/selected/victoria/migrate-ci-cd-jobs-to-ubuntu-focal.html

Story: #2007865
Task: #40179

commit_message:
[goal] Migrate cinder-tempest-plugin jobs to focal

As per victoria cycle testing runtime and community goal[1]
we need to migrate upstream CI/CD to Ubuntu Focal(20.04).

Most of the Tempest jobs will be migrate automatically once devstack
base job start running on Focal[2].

Stable jobs testing stable branch needs to keep running on their supported
distro version which is bionic from stein till ussuri.

Keeping barbican jobs running on bionic nodeset till
https://storyboard.openstack.org/#!/story/2007732 is fixed.

[1] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/selected/victoria/migrate-ci-cd-jobs-to-ubuntu-focal.html
[2] https://review.opendev.org/#/c/734700/

Story: #2007865
Task: #40179

Change-Id: Ief046344957004a5ad29337864ace5837d6c553d

commit_message:
Make identity tests work

Identity JS tests have no output expectations but Jasmine Spec Runner marks
them 'passed' only adding "SPEC HAS NO EXPECTATIONS" into the tests names.
This patch adds callbacks to make tests asynchronous and fix it.

Partial-Bug: #1894127

Change-Id: I6c10c49b6a6aaee2fded8c3ef02f858208bc31b4

[{'created': '2020-05-27 13:35:09.000000000', 'message': 'WIP: Switch devstack base job to Ubuntu Focal

As per Victoria cycle testing runtime[1], we need
to test upstream CI/CD on Ubuntu 20.04(Focal). TC is
in the process of defining this as a community goal[2]

By moving the devstack base job to Ubuntu focal, all project side job
or devstack-tempest job will automatically migrate to the new distro
until they override the nodeset.

As devstack is branched, all the stable jobs derived from devstack jobs will
keep working on Bionic.

Adding multi nodeset also for focal for multinode jobs and also keep
testing the Bionic until we remove its support from devstack.

[1] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/reference/runtimes/victoria.html
[2] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/proposed/migrate-ci-cd-jobs-to-ubuntu-focal.html

commit_message:
Switch devstack base job to Ubuntu Focal

As per Victoria cycle testing runtime[1], we need
to test upstream CI/CD on Ubuntu 20.04(Focal). TC is
in the process of defining this as a community goal[2]

By moving the devstack base job to Ubuntu focal, all project side job
or devstack-tempest job will automatically migrate to the new distro
until they override the nodeset.

As devstack is branched, all the stable jobs derived from devstack jobs will
keep working on Bionic.

[1] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/reference/runtimes/victoria.html
[2] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/proposed/migrate-ci-cd-jobs-to-ubuntu-focal.html

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/738328/

Story: #2007865
Task: #40212

Change-Id: I63e69e898376e728eaf6d857426276fc93a1a0e3

commit_message:
Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/victoria

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/victoria branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

commit_message:
Fix image build when installing agent from package

There is a bug in the octavia-lib DIB element where it runs install
actions that should only be ran when the amphora-agent is installed from
source. This issue causes the amphora image build to fail when
installing the amphora-agent from distribution packages (option -p in
the diskimage-create.sh tool).

Task: 40870
Story: 2008138

Change-Id: I46ba7798322f24255ab7d49db4b4df886e92cbf3

commit_message:
Make message parsing more resilient

Firmware from some vendors only includes the MessageKey in the
MessageID. In this case, fall back to finding the MessageKey first in
the Messages MessageRegistryFile and then in the BaseMessages
MessageRegistryFile.

If the message can't be found, then set the parsed message to 'unknown'
instead of throwing an exception.

If there are not enough arguments to populate the message, then
populate the missing arguments with 'unknown'.

commit_message:
Fix: Remove wrong constraint in vnf_package_vnfd

Currently, vnf_package_vnfd table has a following constraint
in database created by tacker db migration.
This is incorrect, so this patch remove the constraint.

CONSTRAINT `CONSTRAINT_1` CHECK (`deleted` in (0,1))

This is created because `deleted` was boolean before.
`deleted` is varchar(36) now, so db migration change its type
by alter_column method. But this does not remove check constraint.
This patch add drop_constraint to remove the constraint.

Change-Id: I7a62ecf3eeec2f363d0f099bb46d3dec7948501a
Closes-Bug: #1886622
Signed-off-by: Toshiaki Takahashi <ts-takahashi@nec.com>

commit_message:
Add nova-ceph-multistore job in devstack gate

nova-ceph-multistore is defined in nova side to test the
glance multistore on ceph and it is voting on nova gate.

There are other multistore testing enhancement going on for
example- https://review.opendev.org/#/c/743800/. so to avoid
any regression, let's run exiting mutistore job on devstack
gate too.

Change-Id: Ie82b4057463df4b6138c53b14a582bd84866aebd

commit_message:
Bump hacking min version to 3.0.1

hacking 3.0.1 fix the pinning of flake8 to avoid bringing in a new
version with new checks.

bumping the min version for hacking so that any older hacking versions
which auto adopt the new checks are not used.

Change-Id: Icffc9ff0b4f18b9b5981b07774a130f1bdf6ea89

commit_message:
Lower default verbosity for ansible

Similar to aef369e7b4d38e4ca7eb158d2878e84a4b93e603 however this only
affects the ansible-playbook execution. By default openstack cli sets
verbosity to 1 so we are always running ansible-playbook with a -v. This
can a consequence on the information returned during execution as we may
get extra result data in the output.

Change-Id: I4e1cb6658172a7da5ae5198ba55d47de33282975
(cherry picked from commit e8e2ca479faaf96763ba5b27af06a73ebdb5c6c3)

commit_message:
Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/victoria

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/victoria branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: Ifa8dcf40e241662e7762e92595e61fd293d28a93

commit_message:
Install current ARA version into the ansible-runtime venv

Modern ARA no longer has ansible in its requirements file so we can remove
also passing ANSIBLE_PACKAGE to the installation command. We will already
have ansible / ansible-base in the ansible-runtime venv from previous
steps in bootstrap-ansible.sh
Change-Id: Ic7840d4c64b49c2eccea3dba4798cb5b26b2594c

commit_message:
Build timeout as CLI arg for container image build

In https://review.opendev.org/#/c/678907/ it was suggested that the
timeout be a CLI arg. And at present the ppc64le RDO container build job
needs quite a big timeout.

Change-Id: I6bf5238864228c54c84b22b567d873cf29f0e82c

[{'created': '2020-06-17 22:03:24.000000000', 'message': 'Disallow duplicate manage operations correctly

The share "manage" API checks whether
an existing/known share is being imported by
matching the export path provided to existing
shares. This lookup does not consider the
fact that shares may have multiple export
locations, because it relies on an old/deprecated
"export_location" property on shares which
was added to provide backwards compatibility
to the API that presented only one export
location per share.

Fix the lookup by using the "export_location_path"
based lookup which is faster, since it performs
a meaningful join on the export locations table.

Closes-Bug: #1848608
Change-Id: Iaa04b7eac2ebe7aae5637e6ff5d3ef68d3a2dba6
Signed-off-by: Goutham Pacha Ravi <gouthampravi@gmail.com>
'}]
commit_message:
Disallow duplicate manage operations correctly

The share "manage" API checks whether
an existing/known share is being imported by
matching the export path provided to existing
shares. This lookup does not consider the
fact that shares may have multiple export
locations, because it relies on an old/deprecated
"export_location" property on shares which
was added to provide backwards compatibility
to the API that presented only one export
location per share.

Fix the lookup by using the "export_location_path"
based lookup which is faster, since it performs
a meaningful join on the export locations table.

Closes-Bug: #1848608
Change-Id: Iaa04b7eac2ebe7aae5637e6ff5d3ef68d3a2dba6
Signed-off-by: Goutham Pacha Ravi <gouthampravi@gmail.com>

commit_message:
CentOS: Keep repo files during tests

The content in RDO tends to get updated frequenty, and this sometimes
causes unexpected change during tests.
Let's make sure that repo file is not updated during tests, so that
we don't get failure caused by broken idempotency.

Depends-on: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/752594/
Change-Id: I88bee4f7f2c9f5a4178ba41b5f1ed3c8e818e1c3

Zuul encountered a syntax error while parsing its configuration in the
repo openstack/devstack on branch master.  The error was:

  The nodeset "openstack-single-node-focal" was not found.

The error appears in the following job stanza:

  job:
      name: devstack-minimal
      parent: devstack-base
      description: |
        Minimal devstack base job, intended for use by jobs that need
        less than the normal minimum set of required-projects.
      nodeset: openstack-single-node-focal
      required-projects:
        - opendev.org/openstack/requirements
      vars:
        devstack_localrc:
          # Multinode specific settings
          SERVICE_HOST: "{{ hostvars['controller']['nodepool']['private_ipv4'] }}"
          HOST_IP: "{{ hostvars['controller']['nodepool']['private_ipv4'] }}"
          PUBLIC_BRIDGE_MTU: '{{ external_bridge_mtu }}'
        devstack_services:
          # Shared services
          dstat: true
          etcd3: true
          memory_tracker: true
          mysql: true
          rabbit: true
      group-vars:
        subnode:
          devstack_services:
            # Shared services
            dstat: true
            memory_tracker: true
          devstack_localrc:
            # Multinode specific settings
            HOST_IP: "{{ hostvars[inventory_hostname]['nodepool']['private_ipv4'] }}"
            SERVICE_HOST: "{{ hostvars['controller']['nodepool']['private_ipv4'] }}"
            PUBLIC_BRIDGE_MTU: '{{ external_bridge_mtu }}'
            # Subnode specific settings
            DATABASE_TYPE: mysql
            RABBIT_HOST: "{{ hostvars['controller']['nodepool']['private_ipv4'] }}"
            DATABASE_HOST: "{{ hostvars['controller']['nodepool']['private_ipv4'] }}"

  in "openstack/devstack/.zuul.yaml@master", line 388, column 3'}, {'account_id': 26515, 'date': '2020-09-03 18:50:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

'}, {'created': '2020-09-03 11:24:10.000000000', 'message': "libvirt: Bump MIN_{LIBVIRT,QEMU}_VERSION and NEXT_MIN_{LIBVIRT,QEMU}_VERSION

Ia18e9be4d07b732afd9db0007c541253f3cdaf82 bumped these versions in
Ussuri and while it's late in the Victoria cycle we now need to do the
same. Based on the LibvirtDistroSupportMatrix wiki page [1] the
following versions have been selected for the next min versions during
the Wallaby release:

NEXT_MIN_LIBVIRT_VERSION = (6, 0, 0)
NEXT_MIN_QEMU_VERSION = (4, 2, 0)

Follow up patches will remove the following constants after this change:

- MIN_LIBVIRT_FILE_BACKED_DISCARD_VERSION
- MIN_{LIBVIRT,QEMU}_NATIVE_TLS_VERSION
- MIN_LIBVIRT_BETTER_SIGKILL_HANDLING
- MIN_LIBVIRT_VIDEO_MODEL_VERSIONS
- MIN_{LIBVIRT,QEMU}_PMEM_SUPPORT

This change depends on the following devstack change introducing the
Ussuri UCA that introduces the required new QEMU and libvirt versions
while Bionic nodes are used in the gate:

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/747123/

[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LibvirtDistroSupportMatrix

Change-Id: I8e349849db0b1a540d295c903f1470917b82fd97
"}, {'created': '2020-09-03 14:11:10.000000000', 'message': "libvirt: Bump MIN_{LIBVIRT,QEMU}_VERSION and NEXT_MIN_{LIBVIRT,QEMU}_VERSION

commit_message:
libvirt: Bump MIN_{LIBVIRT,QEMU}_VERSION and NEXT_MIN_{LIBVIRT,QEMU}_VERSION

Ia18e9be4d07b732afd9db0007c541253f3cdaf82 bumped these versions in
Ussuri and while it's late in the Victoria cycle we now need to do the
same. Based on the LibvirtDistroSupportMatrix wiki page [1] the
following versions have been selected for the next min versions during
the Wallaby release:

NEXT_MIN_LIBVIRT_VERSION = (6, 0, 0)
NEXT_MIN_QEMU_VERSION = (4, 2, 0)

MIN_QEMU_VTPM is removed as part of this patch as it also requires
changes to functional tests that would otherwise fail.

Follow up patches will remove the following constants after this change:

- MIN_LIBVIRT_FILE_BACKED_DISCARD_VERSION
- MIN_{LIBVIRT,QEMU}_NATIVE_TLS_VERSION
- MIN_LIBVIRT_BETTER_SIGKILL_HANDLING
- MIN_LIBVIRT_VIDEO_MODEL_VERSIONS
- MIN_{LIBVIRT,QEMU}_PMEM_SUPPORT

This change depends on the following devstack change that introduces the
use of the Train UCA on Bionic nodes, allowing us to bump versions here
ahead of a move to Focal.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/747123/

[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LibvirtDistroSupportMatrix

Change-Id: I8e349849db0b1a540d295c903f1470917b82fd97

unarchive command fails. Make config dir absolute path
with os.path.abspath().

commit_message:
VMware: Set fcd backing vmdk uuid to volume id

The symlinks in /dev/disk/by-id/ (in a Linux guest OS running in
VMware ESX based Nova instance) use UUID of virtual disk as the
SCSI device ID when disk.EnableUUID is set to True in the virtual
machine configuration file. FCD doesn't have a native API to set
the backing vmdk uuid. Using VirtualDiskManager API to set the
backing vmdk uuid to volume id. This allows to identify the disk
device corresponding to a given volume from the guest OS.

Change-Id: Ie9bac272a7a94e68ae38cdec5ae695f0e94b698a

commit_message:
VMware: Refactor copy_image_to_volume

Refactoring copy_image_to_volume in the FCD driver to use existing
logic in the vmdk driver to reduce duplicate code. The new methods
introduced in this patch will be used for implementing manage_existing
API.

Change-Id: I92851052d6dc1a3fdd39c3f84809d658d83af1a5

Update master for stable/victoria

Add file to the reno documentation build to show release notes for
stable/victoria.

Use pbr instruction to increment the minor version number
automatically so that master versions are higher than the versions on
stable/victoria.

commit_message:
VMware: Extend volume after restore

Restoring backup to an existing volume reduces the backend
volume size if the backup size is smaller than the current
volume size. Calling virtual disk extend during terminate
connection to fix this.

Closes-bug: 1814346
Depends-On: Ib3d5c115f9076c19c3e33eaf6cccf630439a4c26
Change-Id: I0cbce7829fe09ad1e2843c83e551275196d013e2

Is there a tool which converts customer's custom nic config's to use OS::Heat::Value? We must consider everything under network/config/ examples that the end-user render using process-templates and then copy+customizations."}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2020-09-17 09:31:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> Is there a tool which converts customer's custom nic config's to use OS::Heat::Value?

We'll add one, it should be very simple. I'm little unsure atm how we convert customer nic configs (to simple config yaml), that has number of heat resources with yaql and port resources."}, {'account_id': 18575, 'date': '2020-09-18 09:51:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

> We'll add one, it should be very simple. I'm little unsure atm how we convert customer nic configs (to simple config yaml), that has number of heat resources with yaql and port resources.

I hope you had a tool which you might have used to create these 42 file changes."}, {'account_id': 24245, 'date': '2020-09-18 20:38:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> I'm little unsure atm how
 > we convert customer nic configs (to simple config yaml), that has
 > number of heat resources with yaql and port resources.

Can you elaborate what you mean by "simple config yaml"?
We may need to a spec?

Remember that we have customers that add custom heat parameters to their templates, which they then set values for in environment files. We even document[1] that customer should do this. I.e we cant have a "static" convertions tool, Heat parameter <-> ansible_var. We would have to read the stack environment to get values for custom parameters as well.

https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_openstack_platform/13/html/spine_leaf_networking/configuring-the-overcloud#assigning-routes-for-roles'}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2020-09-19 01:53:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> Can you elaborate what you mean by "simple config yaml"?
What I meant is to a format like in https://review.opendev.org/#/c/752367/7/tripleo_ansible/roles/tripleo_network_config/templates/undercloud.j2

Customers can stay with heat format or move to the simple format. But that automated conversion would not be that easy when yaql and port resources are in network config heat template.

The schema would be same as https://github.com/openstack/os-net-config/blob/master/os_net_config/schema.yaml

> we cant have a "static" convertions tool, Heat parameter <-> ansible_var. We would have to read the stack environment to get values for custom parameters as well.

I think we've an interface ExtraGroupVars[1] that customers can leverage to pass any custom vars used (like custom heat parameters).

I though we're addressing a customer pain point here i.e they don't like current heat config templates (as mentioned in the doc prepared by Emilien). If they don't like it they will move to a new format without heat, right?
I agree this is a big change, but I think is the'}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2020-09-19 03:24:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Missed the link to ExtraGroupVars[1] in the last comment.

[1] https://opendev.org/openstack/tripleo-heat-templates/src/branch/master/overcloud.j2.yaml#L274'}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2020-09-19 08:59:39.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3: Patch Set 2 was rebased.'}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2020-09-19 09:06:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

> I hope you had a tool which you might have used to create these 42 file changes.

Yes, but it's very rudimentary handling one file at a time. Pushed it[1] for now. We can possibly improve it later.

[1] https://review.opendev.org/752787"}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2020-09-19 15:02:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

recheck-rdo'}, {'account_id': 24245, 'date': '2020-09-20 13:27:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

> > Can you elaborate what you mean by "simple config yaml"?
 > What I meant is to a format like in https://review.opendev.org/#/c/752367/7/tripleo_ansible/roles/tripleo_network_config/templates/undercloud.j2
 > 
 > Customers can stay with heat format or move to the simple format.

Ok, good we don't force customers to switch from heat template.
The ansible j2 template format looks okay for something simple like the undercloud or standalone, but I'm worried we will end up with something just as bad for the more advanced configurations. A good example of ansible j2 turning things to the worse, is for example: https://opendev.org/openstack/tripleo-ansible/src/branch/master/tripleo_ansible/roles/tripleo_hieradata/templates/vip_data.j2 


 > But that automated conversion would not be that easy when yaql and
 > port resources are in network config heat template.
 > 

I'm not aware of any port resources in any nic templates, we do some yaql to calculate the maximum and minimum MTU values. In ansible j2 we could do that with the |min / |max list filters? See: https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/latest/user_guide/playbooks_filters.html#list-filters

 > The schema would be same as https://github.com/openstack/os-net-config/blob/master/os_net_config/schema.yaml
 > 
 > > we cant have a "static" convertions tool, Heat parameter <->
 > ansible_var. We would have to read the stack environment to get
 > values for custom parameters as well.
 > 
 > I think we've an interface ExtraGroupVars[1] that customers can
 > leverage to pass any custom vars used (like custom heat
 > parameters).
 > 

Yes, it's the tool to convert I'm woried about. How we find custom var's and migrate them to ExtraGroupVars.

But if we can keep compatible with Heat templates then that is'nt so much an issue.

 > I though we're addressing a customer pain point here i.e they don't
 > like current heat config templates (as mentioned in the doc
 > prepared by Emilien). If they don't like it they will move to a new
 > format without heat, right?
 > I agree this is a big change, but I think is the

I'm worried we just end up with another format that need the same learning curve. Which will frustrate existing users. This is why I think we should explore it in a spec? How does ansible.j2 template look to replicate for exampel a 2-linux-bonds-vlans? How do we j2 template the ansible.j2 template like we did with the heat templates to provide the tooling for composable networks?




Also, do we need OS::Heat::Value ?

Can we not do just Parameters -> Output?'}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2020-09-20 14:03:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

> I'm not aware of any port resources in any nic templates, we do some yaql to calculate the maximum and minimum MTU values

I've seen port resources in nic config in certain customer cases and yes some of the yaql like max/min can be converted to jinja filters. Customer may have some complex yaql that I don't know.

> How we find custom vars and migrate them to ExtraGroupVars

If customer has additional heat parameters, we can provide guidance on how to move them to ExtraGroupVars and use them in j2 templates. I think that can also be automated as part of conversion tool.

> I'm worried we just end up with another format that need the same learning curve. Which will frustrate existing users

I think it's not another complex format i.e same schema used by os-net-config. Only the jinja stuff may make it complex.

However with the new v2 network data format we're working on, these nic config templates can be directly populated by something beforehand (other than the ips) and it would be simple. Also customer would have the flexibility to update them beforehand and get rid of all the jinja stuff if they want.

> Can we not do just Parameters -> Output?

Technically we can, but you won't see the errors in current yaql and heat intrinsic functions used till you access stack output as part of config-download (i.e stack create/update would be successful in spite of the errors). That's why it's better we use OS::Heat::Value."}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2020-09-21 08:13:32.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4: Patch Set 3 was rebased.'}, {'account_id': 24245, 'date': '2020-09-21 09:19:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2020-09-22 03:14:37.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5: Patch Set 4 was rebased.'}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2020-09-22 11:38:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 24245, 'date': '2020-09-22 11:50:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2020-09-23 02:36:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Retire os-loganalyze

This project has been unmaintained for a while. CI jobs don't currently
pass. Zuulv3's dashboard has largely replaced the need for this service
as well as it renders the logs for us instead.

If there is a need for this project elsewhere it can be resurrected and
maintained by others, but for now lets retire it and move on.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/753398
Change-Id: I476b14c7cd9c49270f67897206ec7ad90643703b

commit_message:
Fix upgrade for snmp

If snmp is not on the undercloud, the undercloud upgrade job fails
trying to stop snmp because it is not installed. Let's guard that until
we can get snmp enabled on the undercloud for rocky.

Related: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/731574/

Change-Id: I078403cc6621e580ba1cff6b9a2a3f68d62f5535
Closes-Bug: #1896248

commit_message:
Mount libpod container volume into collectd container

The collectd-libpod-stats plugin requires additional libpod volumes to
be mounted into the collectd contianer in order to find and track running
containers. This mounts the only additional volume necessary

Change-Id: I0f3fb05d8295f8707ad041debb250f255d20626f
Signed-off-by: pleimer <pfbleimer@gmail.com>
(cherry picked from commit fdf8738614dce83023c25b8580f53aee10898261)

commit_message:
[Glusterfs] Fix delete share, Couldn't find the 'gluster_used_vols'

When we have multiple share driver backends, create a shared instance,
and the list of'self.gluster_used_vols' will only be updated on the
current node. If the RPC request to delete the share instance is sent
to other nodes,'self.gluster_used_vols' will be Cannot find the
information of the glusterfs volume we want to delete, so we need to
update'self.gluster_used_vols' when deleting the instance

Change-Id: I14835f6c54376737b41cbf78c94908ea1befde15
Closes-Bug: #1894362
(cherry picked from commit 41b0b95ef67e6c65df3125f94d2fe56b5a3630c6)
(cherry picked from commit 18623a0eebe223c0208d70310a8d0308460bd355)
(cherry picked from commit 807b10f8dbd45af7ea5d11204b1a1bb2e5a2a9a3)
(cherry picked from commit 017c0c42d330ad870187f48a7f469599746051f9)
(cherry picked from commit 79b837ad6c0b761d6069da299c4c39ecd44dabf2)

commit_message:
VM networking for Neutron testing

In order to test neutron integration, we need to reconfigure
the VM and network in order to operate the VM from a bridge
network that OVS will be attached to, which neutron can
ultimately manage.

We also must begin to collect information related to
OVS status, in order to help preserve information related
to troubleshooting when tests fail.

Change-Id: Ia429e4e3a9a982f1ddde9ddd89524bbfc2949801

commit_message:
Experimental Neutron Installation

In order to support taking of the world, we must support
configuring switchports in order to enable maximum
operator flexibility.

This new role is assembled from the ironic and keystone
roles and is intended to update as well as provide some
variables for steps in those roles.

Change-Id: I806b3eb49c04ba1c28bed7a617ff84c3cde88ee6

commit_message:
use os_net_config Ansible module to configure networking

This uses the new ansible module for network configuration
on the nodes. Aso, converts the net-config-multinode.yaml to
use os-net-config.

Next patch in this series would change the NetworkConfig
resource type to OS::Heat::Value and drop run-os-net-config.sh.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/748754
Change-Id: Ie48da5cfffe21eee6060a6d22045d09524283138

revisions:
[{'created': '2020-09-14 17:17:30.000000000', 'message': "Fix backup node lookup

The node lookup code added in change
I27201319f31cdc01605a3c5ae9ef4b4218e4a3f6
was slightly broken in that we call a method
with a keyword arguemnt which doesn't exist.

uuid versus node_uuid.

It happens, it is a quick fix!

"}]
commit_message:
Fix backup node lookup

The node lookup code added in change
I27201319f31cdc01605a3c5ae9ef4b4218e4a3f6
was slightly broken in that we call a method
with a keyword arguemnt which doesn't exist.

uuid versus node_uuid.

It happens, it is a quick fix!

Spotted on a metalsmith job:

[-] Agent is requesting to perform an explicit node cache update.
    This is to pickup any chanages in the cache before deployment.
[-] Failed to update node cache. Error lookup_node() got an
    unexpected keyword argument 'uuid'

Change-Id: I59ecec65707a2f03918b233f1925395ebe59b8c4
(cherry picked from commit 3426963552966af9feae2c79c7c53ee770a9523c)
(cherry picked from commit 6c696e6b7e7f1ef7cbe99a0c5f960b7dea358cf6)
(cherry picked from commit 3adb19634c4727dbdf78aeb18dc36bafb285c80b)

subject: Update the cache if we don't have a root device hint
revisions:
[{'created': '2020-09-14 17:08:28.000000000', 'message': "Update the cache if we don't have a root device hint

Or at least try to.

Some deployments just don't use root device hints, and this is okay.

However, other deployments need root device hints, and with fast
track mode in ramdisks, we created a situation where the node cache
could be updated by a human or software between the time the agent
was started, and the deployment was requested.

As a result, the agent has been updated to check if we have a hint

commit_message:
Update the cache if we don't have a root device hint

Or at least try to.

Some deployments just don't use root device hints, and this is okay.

However, other deployments need root device hints, and with fast
track mode in ramdisks, we created a situation where the node cache
could be updated by a human or software between the time the agent
was started, and the deployment was requested.

As a result, the agent has been updated to check if we have a hint
and if we don't, update the cache from the node lookup endpoint.

This is not needed when the inband deploy steps are executed, as
the process of updating the steps does force the node cache to be
updated.

commit_message:
Proposing victoria RC1 for networking-generic-switch

As a courtesy for project teams, on RC1 week the release management
team proposes a RC1 release for all cycle-with-rc deliverables,
based on HEAD. That RC1 will double as the branch point for the
stable/victoria branch for networking-generic-switch.

Release liaison or PTL should +1 this proposal if they are happy
with it, amend this proposal (for example with a more recent SHA)
to match their needs, or -1 to block it until release-critical
issues are all fixed.

Change-Id: Id24776e9f1f3560d70fa0f2f2b3e81a8f53648d3
Signed-off-by: Thierry Carrez <thierry@openstack.org>

[{'created': '2020-09-22 16:38:47.000000000', 'message': "[NetApp] Fix issues with share server migration

This patch is a follow up patch of the main change[1] that adds
support for share server migration in NetApp driver.
It fixes two issues:
- Data motion 'get_backend_configuration' now avoids sending vserver
  configuration, available only in DHSS=False mode, when driver is
  configured with DHSS=True.
- After migrating a share server, all volumes appears with different
  autosize configuration and need to be manually updated to the
  original values. Provisioning options are also being updated in the
  same method.

[1] https://review.opendev.org/#/c/747048/

Change-Id: I28a47417ec5dda0ed1f6c64fae37f5af6ca057e6
Signed-off-by: Douglas Viroel <viroel@gmail.com>
"}]
commit_message:
[NetApp] Fix issues with share server migration

This patch is a follow up patch of the main change[1] that adds
support for share server migration in NetApp driver.
It fixes two issues:
- Data motion 'get_backend_configuration' now avoids sending vserver
  configuration, available only in DHSS=False mode, when driver is
  configured with DHSS=True.
- After migrating a share server, all volumes appears with different
  autosize configuration and need to be manually updated to the
  original values. Provisioning options are also being updated in the
  same method.

[1] https://review.opendev.org/#/c/747048/

Change-Id: I28a47417ec5dda0ed1f6c64fae37f5af6ca057e6
Signed-off-by: Douglas Viroel <viroel@gmail.com>

bifrost-cli: do not provide any release if non can be detected

commit_message:
Proposing victoria RC1 for networking-baremetal

As a courtesy for project teams, on RC1 week the release management
team proposes a RC1 release for all cycle-with-rc deliverables,
based on HEAD. That RC1 will double as the branch point for the
stable/victoria branch for networking-baremetal.

Release liaison or PTL should +1 this proposal if they are happy
with it, amend this proposal (for example with a more recent SHA)
to match their needs, or -1 to block it until release-critical
issues are all fixed.

Change-Id: Ia95b1d4c160a6440d54378d6abb95e235d150ec4
Signed-off-by: Thierry Carrez <thierry@openstack.org>

revisions:
[{'created': '2020-09-23 16:29:49.000000000', 'message': "Update SKS Keyserver URLs

The HKPS proxy on 443/tcp at sks-keyservers.net hasn't been operable
for many months (consistently returning a 502 Bad Gateway error).
Switch to a direct HKP URL on 11371/tcp at pool.sks-keyservers.net
instead, which returns the same content (unfortunately not over an
encrypted connection). The next best alternatives would be to use a
lookup on keyserver.ubuntu.com which misses a lot of the
cross-signing key info, or keys.openpgp.net which only provides a
link to download key material with no additional information and no
signatures.

Change-Id: I5d99bcb261a77e2d557fa31ca199f2eed09583c3
"}]
commit_message:
Update SKS Keyserver URLs

The HKPS proxy on 443/tcp at sks-keyservers.net hasn't been operable
for many months (consistently returning a 502 Bad Gateway error).
Switch to a direct HKP URL on 11371/tcp at pool.sks-keyservers.net
instead, which returns the same content (unfortunately not over an
encrypted connection). The next best alternatives would be to use a
lookup on keyserver.ubuntu.com which misses a lot of the
cross-signing key info, or keys.openpgp.net which only provides a
link to download key material with no additional information and no
signatures.

Change-Id: I5d99bcb261a77e2d557fa31ca199f2eed09583c3

commit_message:
Update scripts-library.sh to grab output when command exists

This patch updates scripts-library.sh to only grab output from btrfs,
nspawn, and iptables when the commands exist in order to aid in
the troubleshooting of (real) failures.

Change-Id: I5c8677d3e8d1e1c6a6486654d532a899b5d0cf29

commit_message:
Define condition for the first play host one time

We use the same condition, which defines against what host some "service"
tasks should run against, several times. It's hard to keep it the same
across the role and ansible spending additional resources to evaluate
it each time, so it's simpler and better for the maintenance to set
a boolean variable which will say for all tasks, that we want to run
only against signle host, if they should run or not now.

Change-Id: Idd1c6c9ad7f5165b8e12e156ab6398b28c5e799a

commit_message:
Delete image when volume driver is not initialized

When volume driver is not initialized, the image service will be
none, so image will still remain in the glance DB.
This patch fix this.

Change-Id: Ida9aae8f29fbb399efb246140598d02ceef230cb

commit_message:
backup, ceph: Use subprocess from eventlet

The ceph backup driver uses the subprocess module to orchestrate rbd
export and import. The normal python module is going to stall greenlets
for the backup duration.

Change-Id: Iac940e2630424830602f4526cf2666e6721504e6
Signed-off-by: Sven Wegener <sven.wegener@inovex.de>

commit_message:
POC: idrac redfish bios?

Just an idea to spur some discussion, since redfish endpoints
don't, afaik, support being posted to on iDRAC bmcs, because a
configuration job must be submitted instead.

Change-Id: I7d0023634275669cc85b0463e9e4ed960e4f0bea

IMO it would be better to loosen assertions than add a lock infrastructure to our unit tests.

I still think it's possible to fix this properly by preventing notifications from leaking to the wrong places, but since that has proven to be quite hard, I think the above workaround is more appropriate."}, {'account_id': 27615, 'date': '2019-01-29 16:45:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> IMO it would be better to loosen assertions than add a lock
 > infrastructure to our unit tests.
 > 
 > I still think it's possible to fix this properly by preventing
 > notifications from leaking to the wrong places, but since that has
 > proven to be quite hard, I think the above workaround is more
 > appropriate.

Thanks for the feedback Eric.
I know it doesn't look right to lock down tests but since it isn't being implemented for a large amount of tests (only the ones having notification leaks), it looks as a safe alternative to me for quite sometime.
Nova[1] and Tempest[2] also use the same mechanism to avoid concurrency failures in tests.
I agree there are better ways to tackle the problem but i don't see much progress being made there and this feels to be the minimal safe change that can resolve the issue for now.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/tests/unit/virt/libvirt/test_firewall.py#L85
[2] https://github.com/openstack/tempest/blob/master/tempest/api/compute/admin/test_aggregates.py#L152"}, {'account_id': 21884, 'date': '2019-01-29 19:36:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Build failed.  For information on how to proceed, see https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GerritJenkinsGit#Test_Failures

- EMC_Unity_FC http://publiclogs.emc.com/96/632796/2/check/EMC_Unity_FC/b886d76/EMC_Unity_FC/949 : SUCCESS in 1h 35m 22s
- EMC_Unity_iSCSI http://publiclogs.emc.com/96/632796/2/check/EMC_Unity_iSCSI/8b4410d/EMC_Unity_iSCSI/906 : FAILURE in 1h 49m 29s

Leave a comment with 'run-dell-emc-unity' to trigger a recheck, for more information about CI, please see https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/ThirdPartySystems/Dell_EMC_Unity_CI"}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2019-01-29 20:16:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Locks in Tempest aren't related to locks in unit tests.  That's a whole different game.

If the notifications are coming from these tests, and you've identified that making these tests mutually exclusive will fix this, why not just mock out the notification send method for these tests and prevent the notifications from being sent anywhere?

This is not much harder than adding locks and would be much more fitting for unit tests."}, {'account_id': 27615, 'date': '2019-01-30 05:02:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> Locks in Tempest aren't related to locks in unit tests.  That's a
 > whole different game.
 > 
 > If the notifications are coming from these tests, and you've
 > identified that making these tests mutually exclusive will fix
 > this, why not just mock out the notification send method for these
 > tests and prevent the notifications from being sent anywhere?
 > 
 > This is not much harder than adding locks and would be much more
 > fitting for unit tests.

Correct me if i'm wrong, my understanding of the scenario is as follows :
The notification loop call is started here [1] which sends notifications in a fixed time interval [2]. Also these notifications are triggered after a certain number of chunks are created [3].
The parallel execution of tests cause the notifier overlap of other tests (mostly with retype in gate failure [4]) with the async running backup notifier.
I think if the backup tests execute isolated then it won't be interfering with the mocking process in other unit tests.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/cinder/blob/master/cinder/backup/chunkeddriver.py#L558
[2] https://github.com/openstack/cinder/blob/master/cinder/backup/chunkeddriver.py#L115
[3] https://github.com/openstack/cinder/blob/master/cinder/backup/chunkeddriver.py#L634
[4] https://github.com/openstack/cinder/blob/master/cinder/volume/manager.py#L2905"}, {'account_id': 27615, 'date': '2019-01-30 05:11:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> Locks in Tempest aren't related to locks in unit tests.  That's a
 > whole different game.
 > 
 > If the notifications are coming from these tests, and you've
 > identified that making these tests mutually exclusive will fix
 > this, why not just mock out the notification send method for these
 > tests and prevent the notifications from being sent anywhere?
 > 
 > This is not much harder than adding locks and would be much more
 > fitting for unit tests.

Yeah, tempest tests can be seen as a reference implementation."}, {'account_id': 27615, 'date': '2019-01-30 05:25:31.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 24863, 'date': '2019-01-30 05:26:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Isolating backup tests

Their appears to be a persistent problem with backup
tests notifier causing multiple gate failures.
We've mocked all leaking notifications but the issue
stays.
This is an attempt to solve it by isolating the backup
tests that calls the notifier using oslo_concurrency's
lockutils module for thread lock and python fixtures
for setup and cleanup.

Change-Id: I87d5ddb6268c89fb9c7462983a92a2df4ce0851f
Closes-Bug: #1803648

commit_message:
Remove oslo.versionedobjects extra install

We had a very old line in our test-requirements to install
oslo.versionedobjects with its [fixtures] extra to pick up additional
test requirements. That extra was removed with
e44431cff6b76d33e8da1812c31069a1075a97a7 several releases ago. Our
installs would silently ignore this, but with the upcoming pip resolver
changes, this will now cause an error installing dependencies.

Change-Id: I6bb5378377dba19cae119ebb3c146732a8b3844c
Signed-off-by: Sean McGinnis <sean.mcginnis@gmail.com>

commit_message:
volume: Introduce extend attached encrypted volume tests

This change introduces an extend attached encrypted volume test
specifically using the LUKSv1 encryption format after issues were
discovered in bug #1861071. The test mostly reuses the existing test for
extending attached unencrypted volumes with some specific encryption
related logic being introduced in BaseVolumeAdminTest.

Note that while attached volume extension is not an admin only operation
the creation of the encrypted volume type is, resulting in this test
being labelled as an admin test.

A ``[compute-feature-enabled]/extend_attached_encrypted_volume``
configurable is also introduced to control when this test is ran.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/706900
Related-Bug: #1861071
Change-Id: Ibf864c608656d0af906bf0859cedf9cd70b3e58f

commit_message:
[Glusterfs] Fix delete share, mount point not disconnected

When we delete the shared instance, in addition to erasing the data
in the share, we should disconnect the client's mount point to
prevent the data from being written in.

Closes-Bug: #1886010
Change-Id: I7a334fb895669cc807a288e6aefe62154a89a7e4

commit_message:
Ceph Multibackend changes

1. Tempest has an option CONF.compute.compute_volume_common_az to make
sure that Volume and Instance are created in common AZ If Availability
zones are used. The paramater is respected when instance is created
because tempest.common.compute.create_test_server() is used but not
respected when volume is created for test purpose. Let's make sure
AZ is set when volume is created if parameter is set.

2. The plain Encryptor provider is not support on ceph backends, the
test test_encrypted_cinder_volumes_cryptsetup fails on:
cinder.exception.VolumeDriverException: Volume driver reported an error:
Provider plain not supported.
This comes from [1] which is called in [2]. The Plain provider will be deprecated
in future completely.

[1] https://opendev.org/openstack/cinder/src/branch/master/cinder/volume/volume_utils.py#L1195
[2] https://opendev.org/openstack/cinder/src/branch/master/cinder/volume/drivers/rbd.py#L877

commit_message:
Clear cached facts based on the tag as well

Facts gathering comes next after clearing the cached ones. Facts
will be gathered if --tags facts was specified. But cached facts get
cleared always, even w/o that tag.

In DCN deployments that may bring errors that can be avoided with
ansible-playbook-command.sh --tags facts. That is because fact caching
needs to be updated when running outside of the overcloud.

Fix this inconsistency so that the facts never cleared nor gathered
until the facts tag has been used explicitly.

Change-Id: I0ef544a18ec868321ebf51a99051b1ed982cd677
Related-bug: #1896620
Related-bug: #1884654
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobreli@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Create interface to create mysql resources via hieradata

This added the "tripleo::<service name>::mysql_user" interface, which
allows folks to create databases, users and grants via hieradata instead
of having to modify puppet-tripleo.

Change-Id: I975d64c73e314159db0f6c1ada14a26491a46d1a

commit_message:
Workaround issue with >= 16.5 when requiring `addressable/uri`

A change made in 16.5 causes an issue when trying to require `addressable/uri`.
This has been filed upstream with this issue [1]. As a workaround, it seems
using `autoload` fixes the problem.

[1] https://github.com/chef/chef/issues/10452

Change-Id: I8cb5de8aed76f3530e4b4b475024e554c8451790
Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/753415

commit_message:
Workaround issue with >= 16.5 when requiring `addressable/uri`

A change made in 16.5 causes an issue when trying to require `addressable/uri`.
This has been filed upstream with this issue [1]. As a workaround, it seems
using `autoload` fixes the problem.

[1] https://github.com/chef/chef/issues/10452

Change-Id: Iae337a8ff1784c46e8171fc54eb00ef28f11561a
Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/753102
Signed-off-by: Lance Albertson <lance@osuosl.org>

[{'created': '2018-12-17 12:24:39.000000000', 'message': "backup, ceph: do not set ceph backups to incremental

The ceph backup driver uses ceph's internal snapshot mechanism for doing
incremental backups. This type of incremental backup is more an
implementation detail than something that should be exposed to the
outside, because it makes handling of the backups harder.

By forcing backups to incremental, if an earlier backup exists, you can
only clean up old backups by deleting all backups, effectively giving up
the safety of backups, and restarting all over again.

The exported and imported diff results in a fully usable rbd image,
which effectively resembles base backup semantics, in the target cluster
and ceph has no problem deleting snapshots that are in the middle of the
snapshots history. By forcing all ceph backups to be full backups in
cinder, we can leverage this to enable easier backup management.

This change effectively flips the logic from change
I22deff68d9376c2ecc88bd2d9d0e1b445d793123

commit_message:
backup, ceph: do not set ceph backups to incremental

The ceph backup driver uses ceph's internal snapshot mechanism for doing
incremental backups. This type of incremental backup is more an
implementation detail than something that should be exposed to the
outside, because it makes handling of the backups harder.

By forcing backups to incremental, if an earlier backup exists, you can
only clean up old backups by deleting all backups, effectively giving up
the safety of backups, and restarting all over again.

The exported and imported diff results in a fully usable rbd image,
which effectively resembles base backup semantics, in the target cluster
and ceph has no problem deleting snapshots that are in the middle of the
snapshots history. By forcing all ceph backups to be full backups in
cinder, we can leverage this to enable easier backup management.

This change effectively flips the logic from change
I22deff68d9376c2ecc88bd2d9d0e1b445d793123

Change-Id: I570245fe59680a9dcbb8baa82963d59b5da25f83
Signed-off-by: Sven Wegener <sven.wegener@inovex.de>

-1 I have concerns about _update_volume_stats().
Currently, we use _update_volume_stats to report capacity info to cinder scheduler.  It only reports the pool's info. Once we add data_pool, how can we tell the scheduler which pool should be used during scheduling.
It is possible that when creating a volume, not enough capacity in data_pool, but enough capacity in pool, or vice visa."}, {'account_id': 15961, 'date': '2018-11-28 08:13:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

(1 comment)

AFAIK the current way to implement RBD data_pool is to set rbd_default_data_pool in ceph.conf which probably means that _update_volume_stats is not aware of the "data_pool" and just checks capacity in the "pool"?

Maybe I should change _get_pool_stats() to return rbd_data_pool stats if not None? I feel like the space usage of the metadata pool is not really relevant since the RBD headers are so small.'}, {'account_id': 20284, 'date': '2018-11-28 10:32:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

commit_message:
Add rbd_data_pool

Add a configuration option to specify the RBD data pool
It can be used to RBD data and metadata in different storage tiers.

Change-Id: Ia6553ecb22c27b50f7cf970bb00229ab3766c2fb

commit_message:
New snapshot_clone_size option

snapshot_clone_size defines the size of the LV snapshot. Useful when
the available disk space on the storage node is limited.

Change-Id: Id5d187f526759f299bfced487376afeddee2cd42

Huawei driver refactor

Huawei driver code is badly decayed and hard to keep maintaining.
This patch implements the Huawei driver refactor, which to make
the code much more clear, reliable and maintainable.

Change-Id: Iffd47554f5bad6088f76b53fb58e3d5711de5a5a

First attempt at a naive implementation for Peer Persistence volumes in the
HPE 3PAR driver for Cinder.

Implements: blueprint cinder-hpe3par-peer-persistence

commit_message:
Adds peer persistence feature to HPE 3PAR driver

First attempt at a naive implementation for Peer Persistence volumes in the
HPE 3PAR driver for Cinder.

This is a cleaned-up version of a patch we are currently using on a
standalone Cinder installation (non-OpenStack). This means that the basic
functionality of being able to create cinder volumes with peer persistence
has been validated. However, a multitude of tests will be required in order
to merge this functionality upstream.

A first attempt at listing the tests to be executed:

- Validation of the "replication:peer_persistence" setting
- Double-check implementation/configuration of peerpersistent volumes
- Validate creation of peerpersistent volumes when one 3PAR instance is
  unavailable
- Validate automatic fail-over of an existing peerpersistent volume when
  a 3PAR instance goes offline
- Validate manual fail-over of a peerpersistent volumes
- Evaluate retype functionality for peerpersistent volumes

Change-Id: Ib17949da132749bbc4fc3ea56e7b497b3fd94127
Implements: blueprint cinder-hpe3par-peer-persistence

commit_message:
Adds peer persistence feature to HPE 3PAR driver

First attempt at a naive implementation for Peer Persistence volumes in the
HPE 3PAR driver for Cinder.

This is a cleaned-up version of a patch we are currently using on a
standalone Cinder installation (non-OpenStack). This means that the basic
functionality of being able to create cinder volumes with peer persistence
has been validated. However, a multitude of tests will be required in order
to merge this functionality upstream.

A first attempt at listing the tests to be executed:

- Validation of the "replication:peer_persistence" setting
- Double-check implementation/configuration of peerpersistent volumes
- Validate creation of peerpersistent volumes when one 3PAR instance is
  unavailable
- Validate automatic fail-over of an existing peerpersistent volume when
  a 3PAR instance goes offline
- Validate manual fail-over of a peerpersistent volumes
- Evaluate retype functionality for peerpersistent volumes

Changed:

- Fixed invalid variable name
- Resolved all Flake8 warnings

Change-Id: Iddc85e417373744fd7e5c678688ff6da58b9523e
Implements: blueprint cinder-hpe3par-peer-persistence

commit_message:
Adds peer persistence feature to HPE 3PAR driver

First attempt at a naive implementation for Peer Persistence volumes in the
HPE 3PAR driver for Cinder.

This is a cleaned-up version of a patch we are currently using on a
standalone Cinder installation (non-OpenStack). This means that the basic
functionality of being able to create cinder volumes with peer persistence
has been validated. However, a multitude of tests will be required in order
to merge this functionality upstream.

A first attempt at listing the tests to be executed:

- Validation of the "replication:peer_persistence" setting
- Double-check implementation/configuration of peerpersistent volumes
- Validate creation of peerpersistent volumes when one 3PAR instance is
  unavailable
- Validate automatic fail-over of an existing peerpersistent volume when
  a 3PAR instance goes offline
- Validate manual fail-over of a peerpersistent volumes
- Evaluate retype functionality for peerpersistent volumes

Changed:

- Fixed invalid variable name
- Resolved all Flake8 warnings
- Fixed one invalid if-clause when replication is not enabled

Change-Id: Ie8ae386ffc00fbb544ab91afbe5268be19ec4074
Implements: blueprint cinder-hpe3par-peer-persistence

commit_message:
Fix: make Intel CNA hardware manager none generic

Currently, IntelCnaHardwareManager inherits GenericHardwareManager
which makes it a new "GenericHardwareManager" with "MAINLINE" priority.
This causes all other hardware-managers with lower priority than
"MAINLINE" never be used. To fix this, make IntelCnaHardwareManager
inherit basic HardwareManager.

Change-Id: I28b665d8841b0b2e83b132e1f25df95e03e7ba10
Story: 2008142
Task: 40882

(2 comments)

Making this change in Cinder code is questionable at best -- it makes it harder to read and it isn't clear that it offers any benefit.  I think we should not do it.  Objects can enforce that the values entered are correct when necessary.  So can unit tests.  Code readability should be a priority.

Making this change in Cinder unit tests is absolutely not the right thing to do."}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2018-09-11 15:51:29.000000000', 'content': 'Removed Code-Review+2 by Sean McGinnis <sean.mcginnis@gmail.com>
'}, {'account_id': 27615, 'date': '2018-09-11 23:14:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> (2 comments)
 > 
 > Making this change in Cinder code is questionable at best -- it
 > makes it harder to read and it isn't clear that it offers any
 > benefit.  I think we should not do it.  Objects can enforce that
 > the values entered are correct when necessary.  So can unit tests. 
 > Code readability should be a priority.
 > 
 > Making this change in Cinder unit tests is absolutely not the right
 > thing to do.

Hi Eric, Thanks for the review.
IMO choosing enum or string is a personal preference of developer, but enums are still less error prone at the code level for any future addition.
I understand the concern of it violating the readability at few areas but it provides a centralized pool of constants and (for the purpose of consistency in code) has already been implemented throughout in cinder.
I can workaround and keep the original strings at some places but to me this change offers more pros than cons."}, {'account_id': 27615, 'date': '2018-09-17 05:35:05.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 21884, 'date': '2018-09-17 05:35:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Replace VolumeAttachStatus strings with enum fields

This change  replaces the string volume attach status with
volume attach enum field.

Ref : https://blueprints.launchpad.net/cinder/+spec/cinder-object-fields
